{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:32:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:32:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17598"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10312"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7796"},{"type":"tags","id":"7798"},{"type":"tags","id":"7838"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team is designing a clinical trial to compare two different treatments for hypertension. They want to ensure their study methodology minimises bias in group allocation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary purpose of randomisation in clinical trials?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eliminates systematic differences between groups","Creates groups similar in known but not unknown characteristics","Reduces measurement error","Guarantees representative sampling","Ensures equal group sizes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEliminating systematic differences between groups\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary purpose of randomisation. By giving each participant an equal probability of being assigned to any group, randomisation helps create groups that are similar in both known and unknown characteristics at baseline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreating groups similar in known but not unknown characteristics\u003C/strong\u003E misrepresents how randomisation works, as it actually helps balance both known and unknown characteristics between groups. \u003Cstrong\u003EGuaranteeing representative sampling\u003C/strong\u003E is not achieved through randomisation, which does not ensure the study sample represents the broader population. \u003Cstrong\u003EEnsuring equal group sizes\u003C/strong\u003E may be a secondary benefit of some randomisation methods, but this is not the primary purpose. \u003Cstrong\u003EReducing measurement error\u003C/strong\u003E is addressed through standardised procedures and calibration rather than through randomisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProper randomisation, combined with allocation concealment, helps prevent selection bias and ensures the validity of statistical comparisons between groups. Common randomisation methods include simple randomization, block randomization, and stratified randomization.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Randomisation eliminates selection bias by ensuring each participant has an equal chance of being assigned to any study group.","Allocation concealment prevents researchers from knowing or influencing group assignments before participants are enrolled.","Simple randomisation, stratified randomisation, and block randomisation are common methods used in clinical trials."],"references":["Weaver A, Goldberg S. Clinical Biostatistics and Epidemiology Made Ridiculously Simple. Miami: MedMaster; 2012. Chapter 5; pg. 20.","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T12:04:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T12:04:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10312"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic